SIMPLE: influence
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Influence
<hw>In"flu*ence</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n"fl⟦usl⟧*⟦eit⟧ns)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[F. <ets>influence</ets>, fr. L. <ets>influens</ets>,
<ets>-entis</ets>, p. pr. See <er>Influent</er>, and cf.
<er>Influenza</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A flowing in or upon;
influx.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God hath his <qex>influence</qex> into the very essence of all
things.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, in general, the bringing about of an effect,
physical or moral, by a gradual process; controlling power quietly
exerted; agency, force, or tendency of any kind which affects, modifies,
or sways; <as>as, the <ex>influence</ex> which the sun exerts on animal
and vegetable life; the <ex>influence</ex> of education on the mind; the
<ex>influence</ex>, according to astrologers, of the stars over
affairs</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Astrologers call the evil <qex>influences</qex> of the stars, evil
aspects.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Canst thou bind the sweet <qex>influences</qex> of Pleiades, or
loose the bands of Orion?</q> <rj><qau>Job xxxviii. 31.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She said : ⟦ldquo⟧Ah, dearest lord! what evil star⟦br⟧
On you hath frown'd, and poured, his <qex>influence</qex>
bad?⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Power or authority arising from elevated station,
excelence of character or intellect, wealth, etc.; reputation;
acknowledged ascendency; <as>as, he is a man of <ex>influence</ex> in
the community</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such <qex>influence</qex> hath your excellency.</q> <rj><qau>Sir
P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>Induction.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Control; persuasion; ascendency; sway; power;
authority; supremacy; mastery; management; restraint; character;
reputation; prestige.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Influence</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Influence
<hw>In"flu*ence</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Influenced</conjf> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n"fl⟦usl⟧*⟦eit⟧nst)</pr>; <pos>p.
pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Influencing</conjf>
<pr>(⟦icr⟧n"fl⟦usl⟧*⟦eit⟧n*s⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To control or
move by power, physical or moral; to affect by gentle action; to exert
an influence upon; to modify, bias, or sway; to affect; to move; to
persuade; to induce.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These experiments succeed after the same manner in vacuo as in the
open air, and therefore are not <qex>influenced</qex> by the weight or
pressure of the atmosphere.</q> <rj><qau>Sir I. Newton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This standing revelation . . . is sufficient to
<qex>influence</qex> their faith and practice, if they attend.</q>
<rj><qau>Attebury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The principle which <qex>influenced</qex> their obedience has lost
its efficacy.</q> <rj><qau>Rogers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 761 --></p>

<p><ent>Influencer</ent>⟦br⟧
